  "text": "The LLVM code generation pipeline consists of five core stages:\n\n1. **Instruction Selection (SelectionDAGISel)**: Located at llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/SelectionDAGISel.h and implemented in llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/SelectionDAGISel.cpp, the SelectionDAGISel class is the common base class for SelectionDAG-based pattern-matching instruction selectors. It translates LLVM IR into target-specific machine code by orchestrating the entire selection process.\n\n2. **DAG Building (SelectionDAGBuilder)**: Defined in llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/SelectionDAGBuilder.h and implemented in SelectionDAGBuilder.cpp, the SelectionDAGBuilder class is responsible for translating LLVM IR instructions into SelectionDAG nodes. This is the first step in the DAG-based lowering process where IR operations are converted to target-independent DAG representations.\n\n3. **Instruction Scheduling (ScheduleDAGRRList)**: Implemented in llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/ScheduleDAGRRList.cpp, the ScheduleDAGRRList class implements bottom-up and top-down register pressure reduction list scheduling. It schedules DAG nodes to optimize for latency and register pressure using priority-queue-based algorithms.\n\n4. **Register Allocation (RAGreedy)**: The RAGreedy class, defined in llvm/lib/CodeGen/RegAllocGreedy.h and implemented in RegAllocGreedy.cpp, implements the greedy register allocator. This pass assigns virtual registers to physical registers and handles spilling when necessary.\n\n5. **Machine Function Representation (MachineFunction)**: Defined in llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/MachineFunction.h and implemented in llvm/lib/CodeGen/MachineFunction.cpp, the MachineFunction class is the machine-level function representation that contains a list of MachineBasicBlocks and manages target-specific function information, register allocation, stack frame information, and other machine-level details.\n\nThese components work together in sequence: IR is lowered to DAG nodes by SelectionDAGBuilder, then SelectionDAGISel performs instruction selection to target-specific nodes, the DAG is scheduled by ScheduleDAGRRList to optimize ordering, register allocation is performed by RAGreedy, and the final machine code is represented and managed by MachineFunction."
